commit.message:
Restructure tests to make it so the same basic tests can be used for multiple engines

This increases the number of tests ran by default from 38 to 62.
This is useful to ensure that Erubi::Engine subclasses have not
broken the behavior expected.
Add Ruby 3.3 to CI and bump actions/checkout to v4
Switch from hanna-nouveau to hanna
Stop testing Ruby 2.2 in CI as it no longer works with ubuntu-latest
Move to actions/checkout@v3
Limit rake gem restriction in CI to Ruby <2.4
Add CI for Ruby 3.2
Bump version to 1.12.0

Add nocov markings around use of erb/escape

This will need to be adjusted after the switch to coverage testing
on Ruby 3.2 by default.
Add mailing_list_uri to the gem metadata

Use erb/escape for faster html escaping if available

ERB::Escape#html_escape will return input strings as is without
allocating new strings if no escaping is needed, which can result
in better performance for such strings. This shouldn't cause any
issues in Erubi, because the result of Erubi.h is only used to
concat to an existing string.
Avoid unused variable verbose warning on JRuby in test
Test JRuby 9.4 in CI

Update memory footprint comparison

Recent features have increased memory usage.  While here, explain
how the memory footprint was calculated.
Update CHANGELOG

Disable freeze_template_literals if `--enable-frozen-string-literal`

Very few people run Ruby with this option but since the README mentions
it.
Bump version to 1.11.0

Fix tests, update documentation and CHANGELOG

Avoid use of keyword arguments in tests to work on Ruby 1.8 and
1.9.

This explains why you may want to use :freeze_template_literals.
Also update documentation for :freeze to explain when you may not
want to use it.

Add `freeze_template_literals` option to avoid String#freeze

`"foo".freeze` generates an `opt_str_freeze` instruction while
`"foo"` when frozen string literals is enabled generated a
`putobject` instruction.

The performance difference between the two is not that big,
but it's still less work as it doesn't have to check wether
String#freeze was redefined.

It also generate much less native code with YJIT.

Add chain_appends option to simplify VM instructions (Fixes #32)

On CRuby, `b = ""; b << "" << ""`  is faster than
`b = ""; b << ""; b << ""`, even though the result is
the same, because CRuby's stack-based virtual machine
adds an unnecessary pop/getlocal_* instruction combination
(getinstancevariable if using an instance variable instead
of a local variable).

Avoiding the unnecessary instructions can result in up
to a 15% improvement for a typical template.

Unfortunately, this optimization is not compatible with
code that swaps the buffer variable, and there is production
code that does that.  So this optimization is opt-in via
the chain_appends option.

The implementation approach keeps generated code without
chain_appends the same as before.  This makes it less likely
that this change will introduce regressions.

A with_buffer private method has been added to handle bufvar
managment based on the chain_appends setting. A
terminate_expression private method has also been added, for
ensuring any current expression in the generated code has
been terminated.  This is needed in the chain_appends case,
as expressions may not be terminated by default when using
chain_appends.

Co-authored-by: Jeremy Evans <code@jeremyevans.net>

Add space after semicolon in generated output

When :escape option is used, this makes the generated code for the
first line consistent in that semicolon is followed by space.

Avoid unnecessary defined? usage on Ruby 3+ when using the :ensure option

defined? was used previously because before Ruby 3, accessing a
undefined instance variable resulted in a verbose mode warning.
As of Ruby 3, it no longer does, so there is no reason to use
defined?.  This results in fewer VM instructions, so this will
improve performance, though the difference is unlikely to be
measurable.

Add a test for no tags with frozen source

This covers a branch uncovered in Ruby 3, since the change to
not freeze interpolated string literals.
Tighten CI permissions
Test Ruby 3.1 in CI

Run specs in verbose mode on Ruby 3+

Remove spec_w task and use of warning gem.
Try Ruby 1.9.3, 2.0, and JRuby 9.3 on GitHub Actions
Extract default regexp to Constant
